# 🚀 ServiceHub Pro Setup & Deployment Guide

This guide walks you through deploying your Next.js frontend to **Vercel** and linking it with a production **Supabase** backend.

---

## Part 1: Setting up Production Supabase

Before deploying the frontend, you must prepare the database using all the SQL schemas we've written.

### 1. Create the Database
1. Go to [Supabase](https://supabase.com/) and create a new project.
2. Once provisioned, navigate to the **SQL Editor** in the left sidebar.
3. You must run the SQL schema files **in this order** to respect foreign key constraints:
   - `supabase/schema.sql` (Profiles & Roles)
   - `supabase/jobs_schema.sql` (Jobs Board)
   - `supabase/proposals_schema.sql` (Job Applications)
   - `supabase/contracts_schema.sql` (Escrow Contracts & RPCs)
   - `supabase/submissions_schema.sql` (File Submissions)
   - `supabase/rls_master.sql` (Row Level Security execution)
   - `supabase/automations.sql` (pg_cron scheduled jobs)

### 2. Configure Authentication
1. Navigate to **Authentication** > **Providers** and ensure **Email** is enabled.
2. Navigate to **Authentication** > **URL Configuration**.
3. Under **Site URL**, add your intended production domain (e.g., `https://servicehub-pro.vercel.app`).
4. Under **Redirect URLs**, add `https://servicehub-pro.vercel.app/auth/callback`. *(Remember to update these exact domains once Vercel assigns you a URL!)*

---

## Part 2: Deploying to Vercel

Vercel is the creator of Next.js and provides the smoothest deployment experience.

### 1. Push Code to GitHub
Ensure all your local code is pushed to a repository on **GitHub**, **GitLab**, or **Bitbucket**.

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Ready for production"
git push origin main
```

### 2. Import to Vercel
1. Log in to [Vercel](https://vercel.com).
2. Click **Add New...** > **Project**.
3. Locate your `ServiceHub-Pro` repository and click **Import**.
4. The Framework Preset should automatically detect **Next.js**.

### 3. Setup Environment Variables
Before clicking Deploy, expand the **Environment Variables** section. You need to pull these keys from your Supabase dashboard (**Project Settings** > **API**):

| Variable Name | Value | Purpose |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` | `https://xxxx.supabase.co` | Supabase Project URL |
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` | `eyJhbG...` | Public API Key from Supabase |
| `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` | `eyJhbG...` | Secret API Key (Found in Supabase API settings) |
| `CRON_SECRET` | e.g. `super_secret_123` | A random strong password you create. Used to secure the `/api/cron/reminders` endpoint. |

> [!WARNING]  
> Never expose your `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` inside client-side components. It is meant exclusively for server-side Next.js route handlers to bypass RLS.

### 4. Deploy!
Click **Deploy**. Vercel will build the Tailwind styles, bundle the Next.js server actions, and launch your application. 

---

## Part 3: Post-Deployment Steps

### 1. Fix the Cron Job Webhook
Now that Vercel has assigned you a real domain (e.g., `https://your-app.vercel.app`), you need to update the Supabase Automation.

1. Go back to the Supabase **SQL Editor**.
2. Run this quick update to point `pg_net` to your live Vercel function:

```sql
create or replace function public.trigger_daily_reminders()
returns void
language plpgsql security definer
as $$
begin
  perform net.http_post(
    url := 'https://your-app.vercel.app/api/cron/reminders',
    headers := '{"Content-Type": "application/json", "Authorization": "Bearer YOUR_CRON_SECRET"}'::jsonb,
    body := '{"event": "daily_reminders"}'::jsonb
  );
end;
$$;
```

> [!TIP]
> Congrats! Your platform is now live. You can access the unified metrics by creating an account and starting to browse your marketplace.
